theorem Topology.interior_frontier_eq_empty_of_isOpen {X : Type*} [TopologicalSpace X]
    {A : Set X} (hA : IsOpen A) :
    interior (frontier A) = (∅ : Set X) := by
  apply Set.Subset.antisymm
  · -- Show `interior (frontier A)` is empty.
    intro x hxInt
    -- Obtain an open neighbourhood `U` of `x` contained in `frontier A`.
    rcases mem_interior_iff_mem_nhds.1 hxInt with ⟨U, hU_open, hxU, hUsubset⟩
    -- Since `U ⊆ frontier A`, we have `x ∈ frontier A`.
    have hxFront : x ∈ frontier A := hUsubset hxU
    -- Points in the frontier lie in the closure of `A`.
    have hxClos : x ∈ closure A := hxFront.1
    -- By definition of closure, `U` meets `A`.
    obtain ⟨y, hyU, hyA⟩ :=
      (mem_closure_iff).1 hxClos U hU_open hxU
    -- But `U ⊆ frontier A`, so `y ∈ frontier A`.
    have hyFront : y ∈ frontier A := hUsubset hyU
    -- Hence `y ∉ interior A`.
    have hyNotInt : y ∉ interior A := hyFront.2
    -- Yet, `y ∈ A` and `A` is open, so `y ∈ interior A = A`, contradiction.
    have : y ∈ interior A := by
      simpa [hA.interior_eq] using hyA
    exact (hyNotInt this).elim
  · -- The empty set is contained in every set.
    exact Set.empty_subset _

theorem Topology.closure_frontier_subset_closure_interior_of_P1
    {X : Type*} [TopologicalSpace X] {A : Set X} (hP1 : Topology.P1 A) :
    closure (frontier A) ⊆ closure (interior A) := by
  -- First, use the existing lemma that the frontier of `A`
  -- is contained in `closure (interior A)` under `P1 A`.
  have h_subset : frontier A ⊆ closure (interior A) :=
    Topology.frontier_subset_closure_interior_of_P1 (A := A) hP1
  -- Taking closures preserves inclusions; simplify `closure (closure _)`.
  simpa [closure_closure] using closure_mono h_subset
